On the Hill 
 
RUNNING OUT THE CLOCK: The fight over annual defense policy legislation could literally come down to the final hours of the 116th Congress. 
 
Trump has until Dec. 23 to sign or veto the National Defense Authorization Act, which he's vowed to reject for weeks. Democrats and Republicans fear that Trump will drag out his veto, giving the House and Senate just a handful of days in late December and early January to overturn him. And congressional leaders are making contingency plans if Trump runs out the clock, POLITICO's Sarah Ferris, Connor O'Brien and Heather Caygle report . 
 
What's the plan? House leaders are discussing bringing members back the week of Dec. 28, but won’t make final plans until Trump formally rejects the NDAA. The most likely scenario in the Senate is to hold the vote on Jan. 3, just hours before the new Congress is sworn in. 
 
Several House aides said the lower chamber will need to act earlier to give enough time for the Senate to vote in case one senator tries to disrupt the proceedings. One aide said a veto override would likely need to be handed off to the Senate by Dec. 29 to ensure senators "can overcome any procedural hurdles." 
 
The president reiterated his veto threat Thursday, repeating his charge that the NDAA is a gift to China. 
 
"I will Veto the Defense Bill, which will make China very unhappy. They love it," Trump tweeted . "Must have Section 230 termination, protect our National Monuments and allow for removal of military from far away, and very unappreciative, lands. Thank you!" 
 
SHUTDOWN SHOWDOWN: Congress is girding for the possibility of a brief government shutdown and weekend negotiations as leaders work to wrap up a nearly $1 trillion coronavirus stimulus ahead of a government funding deadline at midnight tonight. The stimulus is expected to be paired with a full-year government funding package. 
 
"While negotiators maintained they were close and senators said an announcement could come at any time, there were no overt signs of an imminent breakthrough," POLITICO's Caygle, Burgess Everett and Jake Sherman report . 
 
"And though Senate GOP leaders had hoped to do a brief stopgap spending bill to provide Congress more time, Democrats don't want a continuing resolution that would take pressure off negotiators to come up with a deal by Friday night,” they add. “However by Thursday evening, they conceded they will probably need one." 
 
ROGERS TESTS POSITIVE: The House Armed Services’s incoming top Republican, Rep. Mike Rogers , announced Thursday that he's tested positive for Covid-19. 
 
"I immediately consulted with the Office of the Attending Physician and am currently self-isolating," Rogers posted on Twitter . "I am experiencing mild symptoms but otherwise I am in good spirits and looking forward to getting back to work soon." 
 
The Biden transition also announced Thursday that Democrat Cedric Richmond , who was tapped for a top White House post, tested positive for the virus . And the top Republican on the House Defense Appropriations panel, Rep. Ken Calvert , also announced this week that he tested positive last month and has recovered. 
Happening Today 
 
Acting Defense Secretary Chris Miller has an Oval Office meeting with Trump at 3:30 p.m. 
 
Ellen Lord, undersecretary of defense for acquisition and sustainment, will testify before the Congressional Oversight Commission on the National Security Loan Program established by the Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act at 2 p.m. 
Cybersecurity 
 
NUCLEAR BREACH: “The Energy Department and National Nuclear Security Administration, which maintains the U.S. nuclear weapons stockpile, have evidence that hackers accessed their networks as part of an extensive espionage operation that has affected at least half a dozen federal agencies, officials directly familiar with the matter said,” POLITICO’s Natasha Bertrand reports. 
 
They found suspicious activity at the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, Sandia and Los Alamos national laboratories, the Office of Secure Transportation at NNSA, and the Richland Field Office of DOE. 
 
Sen. Deb Fischer , who chairs the Senate Armed Services Committee’s strategic forces panel, said she has requested a briefing from DOE “as soon as possible.” 
 
“I’m troubled by reports that hackers accessed the National Nuclear Security Administration’s network,” she said in a statement. 
 
Senate Armed Services leaders also said the intrusions are another reason to pass the NDAA, which includes a number of provisions to beef up cyber defenses. 
 
“The bill ensures a coordinated response across the whole of government. The NDAA is always ‘must-pass’ legislation — but this cyber incident makes it even more urgent that the bill become law without further delay,” Jim Inhofe , the committee’s chair, and Jack Reed, the top Democrat, said in a joint statement. 
 
Related: House committees launch probe of government-wide hack blamed on Russian intelligence, via the U.S. House of Representatives. 
 
